# Prerequisites
- Ubuntu VM installed and running Ubuntu server 24.04.3
- Local machines with SSH client installed

# 

- SSH key pair (ed25519 is what i used) generated locally
    ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "prower-infra-key"
- Copy public key to VM
    ssh-copy-id <VM-NAME>@<VM-IP>

# Step 1 
    - Verifying functioning SSH server
ps -ef | grep sshd
- confirm the binary is /usr/sbin/sshd
- confirm package:
dpkg -S /usr/sbin/sshd
- This SHOULD show "openssh-server"

# Step 2 
    - Editing SSH server configs
- edit main config
sudo vim /etc/ssh/sshd_config
- check the following lines exist, if they dont write them in
PubkeyAuthentication yes
PasswordAuthentication no
UsePAM no

# Step 3 
    - check cloud-init config (this will override one of the lines)
- edit cloud-init
sudo vim /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/50-cloud-init.conf
- check for
PasswordAuthentication no

# Step 4 
    - Validate SSH configs
sudo sshd -t 
- no output means syntax is working as expected

# Step 5
    - Restart SSH server (keep your running ssh session open until verification)
sudo systemctl restart ssh

# Step 6
    - Verify running configs
sudo sshd -T | grep -i passwordauthentication
sudo sshd -T | grep -i pubkeyauthentican
- expected outputs:
passwordauthentication no
pubkeyauthentication yes

# Step 7
    - Test from clean client with no keys
ssh <VM-Name>@<VM-IP>
- this SHOULD fail with a permission denied error
- you now log in with key-based login
- go back to machine with keys loaded and attempt to SSH in with prior command
- this should now succeed without any prompt for a password, if you have a passPHRASE it may prompt locally


